I am so excited that “You Sound Like a White Girl,” was selected as one of @applebooks “Best Audiobooks of 2022!”

Check out the link in my bio for a preview of the audiobook. ✊🏾. 

@flatiron_books @macmillan.audio @leshneagency 💜💜.

There was a time when traveling around the world was such an impossible dream: Lack of money and papers. 

I’ve made a goal in life to see and experience the world. And I am blessed to have a husband who shares that same passion. 

This was 2 days in Munich 🇩🇪 .  That makes 20-something different countries 🤩🤩. The Christmas markets made it really magical.

“No sé si es casualidad que yo me sienta así
Siempre que tú estás cerquita de mí.”

To be one of the 102,000 people who bore witness to @badbunnypr ‘s last concert of his “Un Verano Sin Ti” tour is something I will never forget. 

That Benito chose Mexico with to close his tour is not a coincidence. He knew Mexico would show up, and we did. We serenaded him. I hope he felt the love. 

What a night. Thank you @sietefoods for making it possible.

This year commemorates 200 years of U.S-Mexico diplomatic relations. It’s a complicated story. But one thing that is undeniable is how the history of our two countries are intricately connected. 

It was a true honor, and moment of reflection, to participate in important conversations about our past, present, and future. 

As part of the delegation we had a powerful visit to @pochxhouse, a community in Mexico City for deported people from the US. It was painful to know that governments on both sides of the border have failed. But I find incredible hope in the people and communities that are working to create a brighter future. 

#twonationsonefuture

This was my first time visiting El Palacio Nacional de Mexico. There is so much history contained in this one building. 

It was built atop one of the most important Aztec sites as Hernan Cortes tried to bury our history. But I love that now the building is painted with murals depicting that exact history. 

The pictures here are mostly of Diego Rivera murals. 

There is so much I still have to learn about our ancestors, their way of life. But one thing is abundantly clear- we were a thriving civilization.

P.S The Palacio isn’t open to the public. It’s like visiting the White House, you need an appointment. We were there as part of a delegation and we went through a lot of security.
It’s taken a long time, and therapy, to enjoy the fruits of my labor. To enjoy good food, delicious wine, Michelin stars without any guilt. We deserve it. 💜.

Having dinner at the U.S Ambassador to Mexico’s residence was exciting, uncomfortable, beautiful, complicated. 

I’ve written about the heartbreaks my mom and I have had at the U.S embassy. How many times her visa has been denied. I’ve written about the pain the U.S immigration system has inflicted on my family. To have access but still not have solutions is a hell of a pill to swallow. And yet, despite all of it, I am still here. 

I am using my voice. I am sharing space. I am bringing my family with me. Sharing this moment with my nephew was beautiful. 

My favorite moment was when Ambassador Salazar called the entire house staff to be recognized- because without them nothing runs. 

Eternally grateful to Equis Institute, and @elsamariecollins for bringing me along this delegation. 

Seguimos en la lucha.

2022 has been quite the year! I have learned so many lessons. Prayers answered, dreams achieved, tears shed. 

Thank you to every single person who has been a part of my life this year. 💜. 

Here’s to an even better 2023. 🥂.

I have loved all the ways in which y’all have interacted, connected, shared my book. Thank you! 

This is a sample of @bookish.millennial ‘s review of my YSLAWG. 💜. 

It’s true- we deserve to just be. 💜.

#ad I’ve been traveling a lot this holiday season! These are the tips I have been following to stay safe and keep my family safer 1) I have my flu shot and updated COVID booster 2) I stay home if I feel sick and get tested 3) I wear a mask in crowded indoor spaces to limit the spread of germs (and to protect myself) 4) I cover my cough and 5) I wash my hands! I encourage you to do the same! Visit Myturn.ca.gov for more info on where you can get your updated booster. @capublichealth #getboosted
Noche Buena 🎄. I didn’t take any pictures of the tamales 🫔 because I was too busy eating them, but trust they were mouth watering- my suegra made them. 🤤.

In 2023 there is only one “IN”: An authentic commitment to myself and our little family. 

We’re Dos Rayas going to be joined by a Rayita in 2023. 🤰🏽. @raya805 😘😘😘

This has already been the greatest story I will one day write about. 💜.

We’ll get back to your regularly scheduled rejecting assimilation, reclaiming our culture, pro-immigrant, anti-racist, program in due time. But for now, indulge me. 

Deciding when and how to share that I am expecting gave me a lot of anxiety. And some of my DMs and comments reminded me why I gave it a lot of thought. 

Ultimately, I decided, with the support of my husband, that I wanted to share this joyous news now. 

I am doing a lot of internal work. I’ve been back in therapy for pretty much as long as I have been pregnant. In reclaiming my identity, history, self, there is also a lot I have to release and wounds I have to heal.

Rayita deserves my best. 

So anyways, I have a lot more I want to share. Including how for most of my speeches this fall I was so sick before or after and I don’t know how I got through it, but Bad Bunny concerts and music helped.

Late last year I shared a story about the future I imagine at the @makerswomen conference. This was the set up to say that the future I am working to create is one where we don’t have to change anything about ourselves to belong. 

Sometimes it’s still a challenge to express all of my thoughts with the same ease in Spanish as I do in English. But a closeness to my mom is something I crave for me and  Rayita- so more Spanish is in our future. 

(I don’t know what’s up with the captions)! The link to the full video and transcript is in my bio.

From speaking to small groups of 50, to auditoriums of 1,000s, connecting with people in real life and virtually is one of my favorite things to do all year! 

As y’all know, I am expecting 🤰🏽and my speaking will be heavily reduced this year. I am so grateful for the organizations, schools, colleges, and companies that have already booked me in 2023. 

Email me at speaking@julissaarce.com to book me. I have very limited dates in 2023. 

Hope to see y’all soon ✌🏾

Truly the best view my heart has seen. 🫶🏾. It’s been a journey getting here. For a long time I didn’t even think this is something my heart desired, but each time I see my baby in a ultrasound, or I feel them move, I know this is God’s gift. Mi regalito. Mi Rayita. 💜💜.

Story time: when I was actually a teenager, I wasn’t allowed to do anything 🥴. Dream come true to go to the mall with my boo on a Saturday 🤣. All my favs are still there: Journeys, Cinnabon, Claire’s….
Home. 💜.

I believe the connection with our abuelitas isn’t accidental. They literally carry us inside their bodies. 

Maybe it’s pregnancy, or being in Mexico, but I have been thinking so much about my Mamá Silvia. About so many of the things she taught me like how to make a fried egg and how to iron, and also how to be strong and independent. 

I was lucky to know my grandma for so many years. How I wish she’d met my Rayita, too 💜.

Two mass shootings, two days apart. This time in largely Asian-American communities. 

These are the victims. Each of them deserved better. 

When will it be enough? We cannot become numb and calloused as to see this as normal. 

My heart is with their loved ones, their communities, and their families. 

My anger is with our government that only ever has prayers, debates, but never any solutions to a gun violence epidemic that keeps adding more victims.

What a special time it was to spend time with my family in Mexico to celebrate baby Rayita. 

Each of my aunts, uncles, cousins, nieces and nephews wrote (the babies drew) messages for our daughter. Letters we are reading to her in the womb and that we will share with her once she is out, and when she is old enough to understand these love letters. 

We feel so loved. So held. I planned a casual gathering with a cute cake and pizza and it was lovely but what my sister planned for me the next day was BEYOND. Sharing that surprise next! 💜.

So you know how I threw myself a little gathering with my family in Mexico, well little did I know that my sister had been planning this amazing baby shower all along!!! To say that I was surprised is an understatement! I was so overwhelmed with emotion. Even more learning how my whole family, even my husband, came together to make it happen, and keep me completely unaware. 

My therapist says sometimes we have to give ourselves the hugs and experiences we want, and not wait for someone else to give them to us- and I think she is right. But sometimes is so incredibly nice when you those you love and who love you give you more than you even imagined for yourself. 

I love you @nay_one1 Mil Gracias hermana por esta linda sorpresa. Nunca la vamos a olvidar 💜💜💜💜.

Check out the book 📖💜

The shooting in El Paso on August 3, 2019 changed me forever. The lack of attention from the media in the aftermath has been a painful reminder of how invisible this country can make us. And at the same time how hyper visible things like “the border crisis” are and how they inspire these types of hateful actions. 

There will never be any justice for the families, for the community, and accountability won’t be complete until this country changes how it sees us. 

My heart is forever with El Paso, Texas.

Our family needs your help identifying this man and his female accomplice. 

On Thursday, February 16th both of these people ambushed my husband’s Tia at the Smart and Final off of Gutierrez St in Santa Barbara, CA.

They essentially kidnapped her, forced her into their car, and took her to her house where they robbed her and her husband of their retirement money. As many of our abuelitos do, they had much of their money at home. 

If anyone recognizes them please contact our cousin @tbh_bennyp He is helping his grandparents navigate this horrific event with the Santa Barbara police. 

Please help us spread the word and get local media attention to help amplify. 

Thank you 🙏🏾. 

We are very lucky that Tia Rosa is physically ok, but emotionally she has a long road ahead of her.

It’s Texas Independence Day- growing up in San Antonio we learned a very incomplete history. Mexico had outlawed slavey and Anglo immigrants brought enslaved Africans in violation of Mexicans laws. Keeping those slaves was a key motivator for Texas to declare independence. 

Knowledge is power. ✊🏾.

The Biden administration campaigned on being different than Trump and as much as they would like to avoid any comparisons, when the policies start looking the same, it’s hard to avoid.

I hope that these are just rumors, because if Biden brings back family detention, he will lose all credibility. 

It’s time democrats stand with the people instead of caving to media and Republican pressures. 

You can never have humane policies when they involve detaining children, with or without their families.

Happy International Women’s Day! 

Being a mother is not something I ever thought I wanted, until I decided that I would not let my trauma continue to rob me of joy. 

And this pregnancy journey has taught me so much about myself and as importantly, it increased my passion to make the world an equitable place for all of us. 

Women, femmes, trans women, and all people who are life givers deserve equal pay, maternity leave, doula care covered by health insurance. We all deserve to spend time with our child. Time to heal our bodies. We deserve to give birth in a way that honors our bodies.

To celebrate women is to want a world that values us— all of us. Mothers or not.

Starting May 7, 2025, we will be required to present a federally approved document such as a #REALID to board domestic flights and access secure federal facilities. 1️⃣ Gather your documents 
2️⃣ Start the application online and upload your documents
 3️⃣ Visit a DMV Office (Don’t forget to bring your confirmation code to your #CAREALID appointment!) 
Apply online TODAY for a faster and easier experience: https://www.dmv.ca.gov/realid 
And remember that DACA recipients are eligible for a REAL ID in California.

Pregnant people grow a whole organ- the placenta- to help support our baby. It’s wild and amazing. In many indigenous cultures, the placenta is considered holy.

I am going to honor my placenta by planting it with a fruit tree🌳. The fruits of labor if you will. 

What have you done with your placenta?

There is so much talk about banning books because kids shouldn’t be “exposed” to certain topics.  But in my experience, kids ask the best questions. They want to learn more. They want to read the titles on the banned book list. 

Thank you to all the teachers who use my books to help their students navigate these conversations.

A week ago our friends in LA showered us and Rayita with so much love that it’s taken me this long to process it. 

We are so grateful for everyone who showed up to celebrate with us. 

We are especially grateful to @carmensandiegola @bricialopez and @amberkoshofer for planning and co-hosting the most perfect shower. 

It really takes a village because there are so many people to thank for every detail. Every detail was a dream- from the cake, to the flowers, to the cookies, snacks, and of course the tacos. 

Our baby is so lucky to be born into this amazing community of family and friends. 💜💜💜.

Recently, when people have asked me “what’s next?” Or “what’s your next project?” I really don’t have a great answer.

What’s next is that I am having a baby!!!! And maybe that’s not enough in today’s world that constantly asks us to produce and produce and produce. 

It’s a scary reality that women face- how to stay relevant at work while on maternity leave. Or while on a reduced schedule. We value pregnant women, but not always assign that value to mothers. 

I’ve written three books and still I feel the weight and pressure of “what’s next?” 

But I am working to unload that weight. To relish in these last few weeks of pregnancy. I am telling myself that if I do nothing else but grow this baby, that is enough. 

Who knows what’s next 🤷🏽‍♀️. But I’ve always figured out, and there is no reason why l won’t this time. 

So here is me doing my best to bask in the joy of doing little.

Let’s get more kids to fall in love with reading! Find out more at the link in my bio or go to  readingpartners.org/volunteer

At least 39 people lost their lives while trying to reach the United States. 

My heart breaks for every single one of these men and their families. 

And let me be clear, this was preventable. As much blame as the Mexican government has for this— and boy do they have to answer a lot of questions, including why guards saw the building on fire and left migrants in their cells. 

But the U.S government, the Biden administration, have just as much blame, too. 

The restrictive measures the Biden admin has chosen to continue after Trump left office, and new measures to “discourage” migrants from making the trip are directly responsible for these deaths. 

“the building holds both migrants who have been detained on their journey through the country and people expelled by the U.S. Border Patrol under Title 42. That pandemic-era policy allows swift removal without the opportunity to ask for asylum.”

Please don’t look away. We have to continue to demand asylum as a human right, because it is. 
 
・・・
#Repost @washingtonpost 

A fire broke out at a migrant detention facility just south of the U.S. border, killing at least 39 people in one of the deadliest tragedies in years involving foreigners apprehended while trying to reach the United States, Mexican authorities said Tuesday.

Mexico’s National Migration Institute said the blaze started just before 10 p.m. Monday in the sleeping area of its facility in Ciudad Juárez, just south of El Paso. Sixty-eight men were staying in the building, according to the government-run institute. Most of the dead were Central Americans, although some were from Venezuela, said President Andrés Manuel López Obrador.

It appeared the fire was sparked during a protest by migrants who had learned they were going to be deported, the president said at a morning news conference. “In the door of the shelter they put some mattresses and set them on fire,” López Obrador said. “They never imagined that would cause this tragedy.”

Read more through the link in our bio.

Welcome to my señora era! 

I celebrate my 40th birthday today. And what an adventure this life has been. 

I bring with me the blessing of growing up in Mexico, the character-building years of my teens, the lessons of my 20s, the beauty of my 30s— all of it has gotten me to this place. A place where I see my reflection and I love what I see. 

There are some rumors that women in their 40s are past their prime- and boy are they wrong!!! 

At 40, I have energy, knowledge, experience, GANAS!!!! 

What a time to be alive! 

40s, here I come! 

Get ready world, because I am!!

I wish I could tell 17 year-old Julissa that everything was going to work out. That while she had every reason to be afraid of the world, she was gonna come out on the other side. 

I am a little EMO in these last few weeks of pregnancy. But I can’t wait to show my daughter a different world. 🥹.

The first time I felt my baby move was such a trip! Like wow there is really a little baby growing inside of me!!! 

As she’s gotten bigger, her movements have changed, less kicks, more wave-like moves. But I still feel her.

Please talk to your doctor/midwife/ birth team about when and how you should start counting kicks. It’s so important!!! 

I talk to so many moms in our community who never knew they were supposed to be doing that. 

Count the kicks! 💜.

On April 8, 2016, I went on a first date that lasted seven hours. In the weeks to come, @raya805 and I went on many dates and I knew he was someone special. 

Two years later, we got married in my beautiful hometown of Taxco, Guerrero. 

And now we’ve celebrated five years of marriage and seven years since our first date and we’re about to have our baby!!! 

I was thinking a lot about everything I tried to hang on to that wasn’t for me. When I finally let go, Fernando came into my life. I am so proud of the life we’ve built together in these short five years and I cannot wait for all the many adventures ahead of us. 

I love you Fernando. Thanks for getting me that burger today 😘.

Books shouldn’t be banned. But I am grateful for spaces like @velshimsnbc and their “Banned Book Club” that uplift works others are trying to suppress. 

“You Sound Like a White Girl” is about rejecting the idea that we should aspire to whiteness in order to find success, in order to find belonging.

Sometimes it’s our own parents, our own community, who pushes us to assimilate. I don’t blame them because they were doing what they thought was best- what they were taught. 

But I am here to tell us there is a different way to find success and belonging.  We can create spaces where we can be ourselves instead of trying to fit into molds not made for us. ✊🏾.

Today, I celebrate my first Dia de las Madres as a mother. Our daughter, Rayita, was born on April 12, 2023 at 2:05 a.m. She weighed 6 lbs. 12 oz, and measured 19 inches. She arrived three weeks early in a fast and furious delivery. There was no, “we can see the head,” or “here come the shoulders.” She was born all at once on the third push. In that swift moment, I was reborn as a mother. 

I finally got to meet her. She is perfect. She is mine. I don’t mean she belongs to me, but that she is of me, of her dad. Of our mothers and our ancestors. This tiny little thing that I wished for almost three years is earthside. She’s made me a mother.

To read the rest of our birth story, click the link in my bio. 🫶🏾.

I had about 20 meltdowns leading up to it. I showed up to the event in tears. 🥺. 

But a warm hug from a friend, a five minute neck and shoulder massage, some awesome new kicks, the company of amazing mothers, were what I needed.

I am so fortunate to have a partner who is the most supportive. Fernando and Rayita waited in the car for me while I celebrated being a new mom for a tiny little bit.

Thank you @shopwss @nikela for creating a space to celebrate us moms to the max.

The immigration system in the United States is unfair and cruel. 

It breaks hearts. Takes lives. Breaks families. Crushes dreams under its feet. 

I am not sharing the other pictures, they are much too painful to see. 

“In a frantic scene along the U.S.-Mexico border, a group of migrants waded into the Rio Grande, trying to bring an infant to its mother on the far bank. They barely made it.

At one point, the baby appeared on the verge of drowning as the men, laboring through a deep, thickly vegetated, nearly impassable stretch of river, held the child face-down.”

The immigration system has tried to break me time and time again. 

But I remember that even on the worst days- when my undocumented status filled me with anxiety and dread- I still woke up the next day full of hope. I danced. I laughed. I lived. 

🎥 from the 2019 @lafayette148ny Unordinary Women Campaign.

We made it out the house without our baby. It took weeks of preparation. 

We practiced giving Rayita a bottle with my breast milk. Then our nanny gave her a bottle on a different day. Then another day, we went to the grocery store alone and left Rayita with our nanny for an hour to see how that went. 

I went back and forth. Was it too soon? We’ve only had a nanny for a couple of weeks and only twice a week. Should I leave my baby to go to a fútbol game?! Was that a good reason to leave her?! 

I had an emergency therapy session because I almost backed out. 

I spent half the game looking at the monitors.  When I saw that Rayita was crying quite a bit more than I am comfortable with, I wanted to leave and get home ASAP.  But I reminded myself that Rayita was in good hands and she was going to be ok. 

And I had a great time, even though we lost. My husband and I shared a beer. We held hands. We connected doing something we both love to do. And that is a good reason to do something hard. 

We’ll make some changes for the next time we go out because even though we prepared, it could have gone better. 

All that to say that motherhood has been wild. And it’s HARD!!! Even with help, it is HARD!!! 

But we are figuring out what works for our family. And step by step moving forward with our new life as parents.

A few years ago, I shared my story with Good Morning America and it came up in my “memories.” 

The part where they asked me what my message was to the undocumented community is as relevant as ever— your worth does not live in papers. You are more than your immigration status. You deserve to dream. 

At 14 my visa expired and my life changed forever. And now here I am at 40, a lifetime later. And though I am a U.S Citizen now, I will always be shaped and motivated by those challenges.

I know it’s a very culturally Mexican thing to do. Girls ears are often pierced before they even leave the hospital 😅. My sister got Rayita the cutest virgencita earrings, which she will wear when she is older or we’ll make a cool piece of jewelry for her to wear. 

But I cried when Rayita got her vaccines so I am not down for any unnecessary discomfort or pain. 

This is just the best decision for OUR family. ✌🏾.

Lately, when friends ask, “how are you doing?” My immediate response is to talk about how Rayita is sleeping, what new milestones she has reached, how she’s eating.  And the truth is right now, how I am doing is directly, if not entirely, tied to how my daughter is doing. 

I felt a little embarrassed when I came to this realization. Because there is such a pressure for mothers to go back. To have their life back. To be their own person again, as fast as possible.

But we are attached. It still feels like we are one. Babies think they are one with their mother, and I think mothers feel that, too. 

of course, I want to find an individual me. But it won’t be the same person I was before. There is no going back. If there is one thing I have learned through pregnancy and my early days as a mother, is that everything will take its natural course. One day, without me even noticing when someone asks me how I am doing I will give a different answer.

It’s #worldbreastfeedingweek and there is so much to say about the topic. 

Let’s start by acknowledging how difficult it is! 

Rayita latched minutes after she was born and I assumed we were off to the races. 

But I was so wrong. As soon as we got home we both forgot how. It was painful. She lost more weight than was comfortable. The pediatrician recommended formula. 

I wanted to stop breastfeeding her so many times. I am so grateful that my doula @monarcabirth and my night nurse @moonval encouraged me to keep trying. They suggested supplementing with syringe feeding Rayita what I pumped. That worked for us to get her back to birth weight. I am so glad they provided us with this option and so disappointed the pediatrician did not. 

I worked really hard to get my supply flowing. I ate all the things.

I have a long maternity leave and I am able to exclusively breastfeed my daughter with the occasional bottle of breast milk. I love doing it. And sometimes I don’t. 

Whether you are breastfeeding, or your supply didn’t come, or you chose formula from the start, or had to get back to work and couldn’t or didn’t want to pump, I honor your journey.

It’s still #worldbreastfeedingweek and now I want to talk about supply! 

I am not an expert. I am only sharing what worked for me to get my supply flowing:

1. A RIDICULOUS amount of water. And I mean a RIDICULOUS amount. I am not sure how much water I drank the first few weeks, but it was gallons. Now I probably drink at least a gallon of water a day. And on days that I don’t, I can def feel my body dehydrating. 

2. Mother’s Milk tea 🍵 

3. Oats!! Overnight oats, regular oatmeal, oats in my smoothie. Oats, oats, oats. 

4. Caldo de pollo. For the first 40 days I pretty much ate Caldo every day, all day. 

5. Sweet potatoes! 

And I really hate it when people tell me not to stress because it will affect my supply, but it’s true 🥴🥴🥴🥴. 

One day in particular, I was so stressed that my supply completely stopped!!! There was no milk AT ALL. Luckily, I had some stored in the freezer, which gave me time to pump, pump, pump, and by the next morning I was good.

And just a reminder, if you have tried everything, and your supply never came, you didn’t do anything wrong. You are still caring for your baby. You and your baby are connected. You and your baby share an unbreakable bond.

I dedicated my book to the people of El Paso. Always for El Paso. This poem for El Paso. 

On Aug. 3, 2019 a white nationalist opened fire in a crowded Walmart in El Paso as “a response to the Hispanic invasion of Texas,” he wrote in a manifesto prior to the shooting. The shooter didn’t stop to ask any of the 22 people he killed (eventually it became 23) for their papers, or if they came to the U.S. “the right way,” or if they immigrated “legally.” That’s because it isn’t actually about legality. It is about our brown skin in America.

I love us. I believe in us. My hope, always, in us.

After twenty years of living in the United States, I became a U.S Citizen on August 8, 2014 🇺🇸 

Today, we took Rayita to get her passport at 17 weeks!!! 

I never thought I’d have any feelings about my daughter being born here- my little anchor baby. I call her that because we are attached to the bed of this land. This is the dwelling place of our ancestors. Today was a full circle moment. 

Rayita will know the story of how my mother gave me a better life, and how in turn, I am giving her an even better life- one free of assimilation. One where freedom isn’t about flags, but about understanding her history, and that of her people. 

Happy American birthday to me- happy passport day to Rayita.

I trust myself
I trust my baby
I trust the process. 

This has been my affirmation every morning and every night this week. 

Rayita is learning so much. She is changing. She is sleeping through the night most nights. She is still holding on to contact naps. She is four months and has already taught me so much. 

I know one thing, family and trees take away the layer of stress as to be able to enjoy the sweet fruit that is my baby.

Sean Monterrosa was just 22 years old, when he was killed by a police officer in June 2020. Jarrett Tonn shot from the back seat, through the windshield of an unmarked police vehicle. 

Sean’s family, his two sisters, have fought tooth and nail to get some accountability for their brother. The bare minimum was to fire officer Tonn, and even that was a fight. 

And now, he’s been reinstated with back pay and benefits. 

Please don’t look away- we may move on from headlines but the families of those killed by police never move on. 

Please support Sean’s family. Follow @justice4sean_ for actions and updates.

Happy 3rd birthday @poderistas 🎂 

Poderistas was founded by some of my favorites. This community has shown me the true meaning of collective power. 

A story:

It was March 2022, my book, “You Sound Like a White Girl”, was about to come out. 

I was so sad because I had gotten so many no’s from major publications to cover my book, news shows to have me on… 

And then…

Poderistas held a beautiful dinner for me & my book- every detail was perfect. 

@evalongoria hosted the dinner, on her birthday no less!

And some of the most prominent Latinas from every industry showed up. And they spread the word about my book. Booked me on their shows. Posted on their socials. 

I was sad no more. I has just written a book about reclaiming our space, and this was what I was talking about. All we ever needed was each other. 

Thank you @poderistas for everything you do for our community. And how you showed up for me. 

Forever grateful. Forever will remember that as @elsamariecollins says, “Our collective power is boundless, and the world is taking notice.”

Even a few weeks ago these things felt impossible: taking Rayita to a sporting event, grabbing a burger, bringing her to a beer garden. But we’ve done all those things in the last week. 

We’ve found the tools that make it work. A portable fan, a sound machine, noise cancelling headphones to protect her little ears. AND our @tushbaby to carry her when she wants to be held. 

Tushbaby is having a sale. Use my code JULISSAARCE for 22% off.

So many moms told me, “it gets easier.” But in the middle of the haze, it was hard to see how it would ever be easier. 

We are almost 5 months into this journey, and it is in fact getting easier. Not easy, but easier.

Maybe it’s her laughs. Her looking up at me with so much love. Maybe it‘s the things we have survived as a couple. The ones last week. The sleepless nights. 

And now our baby is rolling over and sleeping more and has a routine. We worked hard for this.

Our perfect baby, how I am enjoying her. Our little family.  Aquí es donde voy a sembrar. 🫶🏾🫶🏾.

VERY IMPORTANT PSA. 😂.

Mi Mamá Silvia would have turned 94 years old today. 

Rayita is 5 months today. She is my grandmother’s youngest descendent.

How I wish my daughter would have met such a strong, inspiring, wonderful woman in person. But the truth is that my grandmother lives in me, and she lives in my daughter. As long as we keep telling stories about my grandmother, she will continue to influence all of us.

When I forget to put socks on Rayita’s little feet, I hear my grandmother’s voice. “Estas loca mocosa, ponle calcetas a La Niña! Se va an emfermar! “ 😂. 

And I also hear her voice when I have doubts. She tells me “tu puedes Natzely.” 

Feliz cumpleaños Mamá Silvia. Que nos siga cuidando desde el cielo. Aquí se le extraña.

Today was my first speaking event since my daughter was born. (Happy Latino Heritage Month). 

I had so much anxiety about leaving home and leaving her behind.

She‘s only been away from me a couple of hours here and there. But usually she is fed and asleep. 

I was so scared about today that I texted a friend freaking out yesterday since our bottle practice hadn’t been going well. 

I felt guilty for not introducing a bottle earlier. I had been afraid she would prefer the bottle. Was it a mistake? My friend said it wasn’t. Because we do the best we can. She’s right. Not a mistake just a choice. 

But guess what!! It all turned out ok. 👌🏾. She ate. She slept. My husband and our nanny took great care of Rayita. 

It’s a good reminder that we never have to carry the load all by ourselves. 

Super grateful to the event organizers for booking me a whole “mother’s suite”. I pumped before and after the event. 

Every company should have as beautiful a lactation room as this. 

One down, a few more to go! 

Here we go!!!!

UPDATE: THE EVENT AT UNITY PARK IS AT 2:00PM!!!! 

Now that we got the first event post baby down, I am ready for a few more during Latino Heritage Month 🫶🏾

I hope to see many of you in Sonoma County next weekend!! 

I am on a reduced schedule this year, but I have one or two more events in me. Email me at Speaking@julissaarce.com to book me at your company, organization, college, etc.

When I was a baby my mom worked the Ferias in Mexico selling cantaritos and she took me on the road with her until it was time to start school. I don’t remember those moments but I loved the stories she shared with me. 

And now my baby girl is on the road with me for my Latino Heritage Month speaking events. She might not remember when she is older, but I hope the love and adventures stay in her spirit. 

When she is older, I’ll tell her about one poopy explosion in the car 😂. I’ll tell her how my heart could  hardly contain all the love I feel when I get back to her and she smiles because she knows I have returned.

This might be my most favorite LHM because of her. ♥️. 

Also, why do babies need so much stuff 😂. I used to take a carry on for a two week trip.

My favorite is talking to young people.
I love their questions.
Their curiosity.
It also reminds me of how much work we have to do. They shouldn’t have to deal with what we dealt with. It’s time for change. 

Seguimos. 

Next stop Sonoma County!

My event today is Sonoma County was going to take place at Andy’s Unity Park before it was moved indoors due to poor air quality. 

The park is a memorial for Andy Lopez. Andy was 13 years old when he was walking with a toy gun and was shot multiple times and killed by a Sonoma County Sheriff’s deputy on October 22, 2013. 

Today, I was asked by a López family friend why I wrote about Andy in my book. 

In Sonoma County, in Andy’s old neighborhood, in the Latino community here, Andy’s story is known. It was memorialized with this park. 

But outside his community how many of us have heard his story? 

It’s been almost ten years. His parents have had to wake up every day for ten years without their son. 

The deputy who killed him got promoted. He retired with his pension. And how many more Black and Brown kids have been killed by police since? 

Andy’s life should be remembered. If even one person learns and remembers and honors and prays for his parents’ peace, then that’s why I wrote about Andy López. 
 
Rest easy chiquito. 🕊️. We honor you. We remember you.

I’ve had doubts about the impact of my work, but then I get out on the road and I meet you and you show up! You tell me how much my books have meant in your life, and those doubts are dissolved by your words. 

Thank you!

What a beautiful thing it is to be in community! To share space sin pelos en la lengua. 

Y’all are the best. My cup is full.

It’s #nationaldaughtersday ?! 

There is so much to say about being a mom to a daughter. The joy. The responsibility. The way I want to protect her. How I want her to grow up always knowing how much she is loved and cared for. 

When she was very very little and she cried so much, I’d repeat a mantra for her: 

you are loved, you are cared for. Your mami loves you. Your papi loves you. You have everything you need. You are smart. You are beautiful. You are strong. You are kind. You have everything you need. You are loved. 

And it would soothe her. 

Time is a strange concept when you have a baby- it stretches to the point of almost breaking you. It also swooshes by and you want it to stand still so you admire the miracle of your daughter a little longer. 

Rayita stretched her arms out for me for the first time this week and I wanted all time to stop so I could remember this moment exactly as it happened.

Te amo mija. ♥️.

Sorting through Rayita’s newborn clothes and I got super emotional. 

She was so teeny tiny. I was a new mom with very little support as our families are far away. I felt so overwhelmed. I definitely dealt with postpartum depression. 

I was in a haze I thought I would never get out of. 

And for a moment today I felt so guilty that I didn’t enjoy it as much— that I missed so much the first few months because I was operating in survival mode.

People messaged me  to encourage me after I posted a hard moment and they’d write, “enjoy it, it goes by so fast.” 

I just wanted to scream every time someone wrote me that. It made me feel guilty. It made me feel like, “what am I doing wrong!” Why didn’t I enjoy it all the time?!

But I did the best I could. I enjoyed the moments I could. But most importantly I kept my daughter safe and healthy. And my body has given her every single thing she’s needed. 

And now she is still small but not teeny tiny. I am not a brand new mom. I have five of the hardest months anyone can live under my belt. I have so much more confidence in my ability to be her mom. 

And now I am here, able to enjoy so much more of every moment.

Putting her newborn  clothes away is a triumph of what we’ve survived. And I did enjoy some of it because I can even  remember what she did when she wore what outfit.

It’s a reminder that time does go by fast and I want to be present as much as possible. But not from a place of guilt but from a place of hope. ♥️.

Rayita’s first @lafc game 
🖤💛🖤💛 I didn’t want to miss this game. My fav player made a return to LA. 

The last time she was at the stadium was the last day she was inside. I went into labor that night 😂. 

She did amazing! She saw the night for the first time!!! 

Dad and I did ok lol. 

We are learning that no matter what, we are gonna be ok. It’s ok if she cries. It’s ok if she stays awake longer that her appropriate wake window every once in a while. Everything is ok at the end! 

The team lost but @chichoarango (who should still be with LAFC) scored. He didn’t celebrate the goal. When he was asked why not, he said, “for respect for the fans. For respect for the team.” And that among so many reasons is why I miss Chico in Black and Gold.

“Is there a bigger dream than going back home?”

I felt this dream, this desire, this longing for years and years and years.

To go back home. To see my grandmother’s house again. To touch the land that birth me, and my ancestors. What bigger dream is there? 

The fact is Palestinians cannot go home. They have been displaced. Driven out. Forced out. And after the heavy bombardment, what little home they knew is now gone for millions more. 

Cease fire now. Not one more innocent child should be killed. Cease fire now.
………..

When people say you should sleep when the baby sleeps what they don't tell you is just how difficult it can be to get the baby TO SLEEP!!!

I've had so much anxiety about Rayita sleeping that for a while once she went to sleep, Fernando and I would eat dinner in silence and in the dark as to not wake her. When we accidentally left the AC on, we'd run to turn it off because we thought the change in temperature could also wake her up. 
There have been no magic tricks! But with consistency and patience, she sleeps through the night and is taking most of her naps in the crib now (remember all those contact naps?!). 

One thing that has really helped her night time routine since we transitioned her out of the swaddle has been our @woolino sleep sack. We love it because it's super soft, temperature regulating, and safe. 

Every night, Rayita gets her massage, bath, and then into her Woolino sleep sack and off to sleep she goes. Though sometimes there is still a lot of rocking and singing ;)

I am not trying to convince anyone of anything. But I ask, how did we get to a place where we are justifying the killing of 11,000 people in one month, half of them children. 

We point to Hamas as the reason for the actions of the Israeli government as though one justifies the other. It does not. How did our moral compass become that. How are we not screaming every day for this war to stop. For children to live. 

I wake up every morning thinking of what the Palestinian people have endured while I slept comfortably in my bed.

Let the children live.

How is it that calling for peace at a time of war is considered controversial? 

Calling for a ceasefire to spare the life of innocent civilians, including so many children, should not put your livelihood at risk. Yet, here we are. 

I have followed Melissa’s posts and she has called for humanity. 

You might disagree on whether what is happening is Gaza is a genocide, but over 10,000 Palestinians have been killed, half of them children.  Where is our humanity? 

This censorship is dangerous. Especially when the Variety article names mostly people of color as having been dropped from agencies, or powerful people calling for them to be dropped. 

I stand with Melissa. I stand with a free Palestine. I stand for a cease fire. I stand with the families of the hostages. I stand for humanity.

.

THANK YOU!!!! My sister, Silvia Nayssa Arce Aviles and my brother-in-law, Alberto Sanchez Juarez, are now safe and reunited with their three kids. 

I don’t have the words to express the relief and gratefulness I feel to have them back safely. 

Thank you to every single person who prayed, who shared my posts, who sent messages of support.

Thank you God. 

I pray for every person who has experienced this to be returned to their families. 

Thank you to Artículo 19 for all the support and for everything you do to protect journalists. 

To all the journalists that joined protests in Mexico, and who covered the story, thank you.

And thank you to all the state and federal agencies who helped get my sister and brother-in-law back to us. 

Te amo hermana. De aquí al infinito y más allá.

“If I must die, you must live….

Let it bring hope.”

I’ve been sitting with these words by Refaat Alareer. What a spirit one must have to stare death in the face and wish it will bring hope to your people. 

Palestinians have lived through so much—displacement, apartheid, an ongoing occupation. And now they face a targeted erasure of their people. 

And all I can think of is how can the world be watching and let it happen.

Let these words bring us an actionable hope. 

Keep demanding an immediate permanent cease fire. 
・・・
#Repost @palfest

Brian Cox is unable to join us on stage in London tomorrow night - so here he is, reading If I Must Die, by beloved Palestinian poet, teacher and martyr Refaat Alareer.

Refaat was killed on December 7th by an Israeli airstrike.

This was the last poem he published.

His body is unburied under the rubble.

You may have seen this Bill Maher clip… the way he excuses genocide, colonization, occupation as though it was just every day life, as though we shouldn’t bat an eye, is peak white supremacy. 

He needs to read a history book because to offer Mexico as an example of how, “they chose a different path,” is to ignore the severe consequences of the Mexican-American war, consequences that are still felt today by Mexicans on both sides of the border. 

And if things change- as he says- then things should change so that Palestinians have self determination. 

Permanent cease fire now!
